## Logit Softcapping: Preventing Overconfidence

In 2024, Google's Gemma 2 team introduced **logit softcapping**. The problem: during early training, logits can blow up to extreme values. A logit of 50 for one token and -50 for the rest means the model is 100% confident in its prediction — which is almost certainly wrong for an untrained model.

Hard clipping (just cap at ±20) would work, but it kills gradients at the boundary. The Gemma team used `tanh` instead: smooth, differentiable, and naturally bounded between -1 and 1.

`softcap(x) = c · tanh(x / c)`

For small inputs (well within the cap), this is approximately the identity function. Only extreme values get compressed.

```elixir
softcap = 20.0
logit_range = Nx.linspace(-50.0, 50.0, n: 300)

identity_vals = Nx.to_flat_list(logit_range)
capped_vals = Nx.to_flat_list(Nx.multiply(softcap, Nx.tanh(Nx.divide(logit_range, softcap))))

cap_data =
  Enum.zip(identity_vals, capped_vals)
  |> Enum.flat_map(fn {raw, capped} ->
    [
      %{"logit" => Float.round(raw, 2), "output" => Float.round(raw, 2), "function" => "Identity (no cap)"},
      %{"logit" => Float.round(raw, 2), "output" => Float.round(capped, 4), "function" => "Softcap (c=20)"}
    ]
  end)

Vl.new(width: 500, height: 300, title: "Logit Softcapping: smooth, differentiable, bounded")
|> Vl.data_from_values(cap_data)
|> Vl.mark(:line)
|> Vl.encode_field(:x, "logit", type: :quantitative, title: "Raw logit")
|> Vl.encode_field(:y, "output", type: :quantitative, title: "Output")
|> Vl.encode_field(:color, "function", type: :nominal)
```

Notice: within [-10, 10], the softcapped line is almost identical to identity. Only beyond ±15 does the compression become visible. The model barely notices the cap during normal operation — it only kicks in to prevent disaster.

```elixir
IO.puts("Near-identity property:\n")

for val <- [-5.0, -1.0, 0.0, 1.0, 5.0, 10.0, 20.0, 30.0, 50.0] do
  capped = softcap * :math.tanh(val / softcap)
  diff = abs(val - capped)
  IO.puts("  logit=#{String.pad_leading(Float.to_string(val), 6)} -> capped=#{String.pad_leading(Float.to_string(Float.round(capped, 3)), 8)}  diff=#{Float.round(diff, 4)}")
end
```

### Verify Against the v2 Model

```elixir
test_logits = Nx.tensor([[-30.0, -5.0, 0.0, 5.0, 30.0]])

reference = ExNanoGPT.V2.Model.softcap_logits(test_logits)
ours = Nx.multiply(20.0, Nx.tanh(Nx.divide(test_logits, 20.0)))

diff = Nx.subtract(ours, reference) |> Nx.abs() |> Nx.reduce_max() |> Nx.to_number()
IO.puts(if diff < 1.0e-5, do: "MATCH! Max diff: #{diff}", else: "MISMATCH. Max diff: #{diff}")
```

## Value Embeddings: The 44% Surprise

Here's something remarkable about Karpathy's nanochat architecture. In October 2024, Loshchilov et al. at NVIDIA published **nGPT**, a transformer where all vectors live on a hypersphere. Part of this idea — giving each layer an additional "value embedding" looked up by token identity — made its way into nanochat.

In nanochat's record-setting model, **value embeddings account for 604 million out of 1.38 billion parameters** — nearly 44% of the entire model.

The idea: on alternating layers, look up a learned vector for each token (like the input embedding, but separate) and add it to V. This gives the attention mechanism a direct signal about *what* each token is, independent of the surrounding context.

```elixir
config = ExNanoGPT.V2.Model.tiny_config()

IO.puts("Which layers get value embeddings?\n")
for i <- 0..(config.n_layer - 1) do
  has_ve = ExNanoGPT.V2.Model.has_ve?(i, config.n_layer)
  IO.puts("  Layer #{i}: #{if has_ve, do: "YES (value embeddings)", else: "no"}")
end

ve_params = config.vocab_size * config.n_kv_head * div(config.n_embd, config.n_head)
layers_with_ve = Enum.count(0..(config.n_layer - 1), &ExNanoGPT.V2.Model.has_ve?(&1, config.n_layer))
total_ve = ve_params * layers_with_ve
IO.puts("\nValue embedding params per layer: #{ve_params}")
IO.puts("Layers with VE: #{layers_with_ve}")
IO.puts("Total VE params: #{total_ve}")
IO.puts("Gate channels: #{ExNanoGPT.V2.Model.ve_gate_channels()}")
```

## Per-Layer Residual Scaling

In v1, the residual connection is simple: `x = x + block(x)`. In v2, each layer first applies per-layer scaling:

`x = λ_r · x + λ_0 · x₀`

where x₀ is the initial embedding (saved after the first RMSNorm). This gives the model fine-grained control over how much of the original signal survives at each depth. The x₀ skip acts as a "gradient highway" — gradients flow directly from the loss back to the embeddings, making deep networks trainable.

```elixir
n_layers = 6
resid_lambdas = Nx.broadcast(Nx.tensor(1.0, type: :f32), {n_layers})
x0_lambdas = Nx.broadcast(Nx.tensor(0.1, type: :f32), {n_layers})

IO.puts("At each layer:")
IO.puts("  x = #{Nx.to_number(resid_lambdas[0])} * x + #{Nx.to_number(x0_lambdas[0])} * x0")
IO.puts("\nThe running state x gets full weight (1.0).")
IO.puts("The original embedding x0 gets a small influence (0.1).")
IO.puts("These lambdas are learnable — the model discovers the right balance during training.")
```

## The Full Forward Pass

Here's the complete architecture. Every piece — RMSNorm, RoPE, GQA, QK norm, sliding window, ReLU-squared, value embeddings, residual scaling, softcapping — assembled into one forward pass.

```
Input token IDs: {batch, seq_len}
        |
        v
   Token Embedding (wte)        <- {vocab_size, n_embd}
        |
        v
   RMSNorm (embed)
        |
        +--- save as x0 (for skip connections)
        |
        v
  +------------- Layer i ---------------+
  |  x = lambda_r * x + lambda_0 * x0  |  <- per-layer scaling
  |  x_norm = RMSNorm(x)               |
  |  Q = x_norm * W_Q      (n_head)    |
  |  K = x_norm * W_K      (n_kv_head) |
  |  V = x_norm * W_V + VE (n_kv_head) |  <- value embeddings on alt layers
  |  Q, K = RoPE(Q, K)                 |
  |  Q, K = RMSNorm(Q), RMSNorm(K)     |  <- QK normalization
  |  K, V = expand_heads(K, V)          |  <- GQA head expansion
  |  attn = softmax(Q*K^T/sqrt(d)+mask)*V|  <- sliding window mask
  |  x = x + attn * W_proj             |
  |  x = x + ReLU²(RMSNorm(x)*W_fc)*W_p|
  +-------------------------------------+
        |                    x n_layer
        v
   RMSNorm (final)
        |
        v
   Linear (lm_head)             <- {vocab_size, n_embd}, untied from wte
        |
        v
   Softcap: 20*tanh(logits/20)
        |
        v
   Output logits: {batch, seq_len, vocab_size}
```

### Initialize and Run

```elixir
config = ExNanoGPT.V2.Model.tiny_config()
key = Nx.Random.key(1337)
params = ExNanoGPT.V2.Model.init_params(config, key)

IO.puts("v2 Model Config:")
IO.puts("  vocab_size:   #{config.vocab_size}")
IO.puts("  n_layer:      #{config.n_layer}")
IO.puts("  n_head:       #{config.n_head}")
IO.puts("  n_kv_head:    #{config.n_kv_head}")
IO.puts("  n_embd:       #{config.n_embd}")
IO.puts("  window_pattern: #{config.window_pattern}")
```

```elixir
batch = 2
seq_len = 16
idx = Nx.tensor(
  Enum.map(1..batch, fn _ ->
    Enum.map(1..seq_len, fn _ -> :rand.uniform(config.vocab_size) - 1 end)
  end),
  type: :s32
)

logits = ExNanoGPT.V2.Model.forward(idx, params, config)

IO.inspect(Nx.shape(logits), label: "output logits shape (should be {2, 16, 256})")
IO.puts("\nLogit range: [#{Float.round(Nx.to_number(Nx.reduce_min(logits)), 4)}, #{Float.round(Nx.to_number(Nx.reduce_max(logits)), 4)}]")
IO.puts("Softcap bound: [-20.0, 20.0]")
IO.puts("All logits within softcap? #{Nx.to_number(Nx.reduce_max(Nx.abs(logits))) < 20.001}")
```

