v2_count = ExNanoGPT.V2.Model.count_params(params)

v1_config = %{
  vocab_size: 65, block_size: 256, n_layer: 6,
  n_head: 6, n_embd: 384, dropout: 0.0, bias: true
}
v1_params = ExNanoGPT.Model.init_params(v1_config, Nx.Random.key(0))
v1_count = ExNanoGPT.Model.count_params(v1_params, non_embedding: false)

format_params = fn n ->
  cond do
    n >= 1_000_000 -> "#{Float.round(n / 1_000_000, 2)}M"
    n >= 1_000 -> "#{Float.round(n / 1_000, 1)}K"
    true -> "#{n}"
  end
end

IO.puts("Parameter counts:")
IO.puts("  v1 (nanoGPT):  #{format_params.(v1_count)} (vocab=#{v1_config.vocab_size}, d=#{v1_config.n_embd}, layers=#{v1_config.n_layer})")
IO.puts("  v2 (nanochat):  #{format_params.(v2_count)} (vocab=#{config.vocab_size}, d=#{config.n_embd}, layers=#{config.n_layer})")
IO.puts("\nYou just built the same architecture Karpathy used to train a")
IO.puts("GPT-2-quality chatbot for under $100 in cloud compute.")
```

## Break It

> **Predict**: What happens to the range of logit values without softcapping? Think about what `c * tanh(x/c)` does to large inputs.

### Remove softcapping

Without softcapping, logits can grow unbounded. With random weights this is mild, but during training it causes instability.

```elixir
x_test = Nx.take(params.wte, idx, axis: 0)
x_test = ExNanoGPT.V2.Model.rms_norm(x_test)

raw_logits = Nx.dot(x_test, [-1], params.lm_head, [1])
capped_logits = ExNanoGPT.V2.Model.softcap_logits(raw_logits)

IO.puts("Raw logit range:    [#{Float.round(Nx.to_number(Nx.reduce_min(raw_logits)), 2)}, #{Float.round(Nx.to_number(Nx.reduce_max(raw_logits)), 2)}]")
IO.puts("Capped logit range: [#{Float.round(Nx.to_number(Nx.reduce_min(capped_logits)), 4)}, #{Float.round(Nx.to_number(Nx.reduce_max(capped_logits)), 4)}]")
IO.puts("\nSoftcapping guarantees logits stay in [-20, 20], preventing overconfident predictions.")
```

### Set resid_lambdas to 0

If `lambda_r = 0`, the running hidden state is discarded at each layer. Only the x0 skip survives.

```elixir
broken_params = %{params | resid_lambdas: Nx.broadcast(Nx.tensor(0.0, type: :f32), {config.n_layer})}
logits_broken = ExNanoGPT.V2.Model.forward(idx, broken_params, config)

# Nx.standard_deviation measures spread; Nx.reduce_min finds the minimum value
IO.puts("Normal logit std:     #{Float.round(Nx.to_number(Nx.standard_deviation(logits)), 4)}")
IO.puts("resid_lambda=0 std:   #{Float.round(Nx.to_number(Nx.standard_deviation(logits_broken)), 4)}")
IO.puts("\nWith resid_lambda=0, each block's computation is thrown away.")
IO.puts("x = 0*x + 0.1*x0 — the transformer blocks have no cumulative effect.")
```

### Challenge: Value Embeddings vs More MLP

Value embeddings account for ~44% of nanochat's parameters. What if you gave those parameters to the MLP instead? Would the model be better or worse?

Think about it: value embeddings provide a *context-free* signal about token identity. The MLP provides a *context-dependent* transformation. Are both necessary? Why might the context-free signal be valuable even when you have context?

## Architecture Comparison: v1 vs v2

| Feature | v1 (nanoGPT / GPT-2) | v2 (nanochat / LLaMA-style) |
|---------|----------------------|----------------------------|
| **Normalization** | LayerNorm (learnable γ, β) | RMSNorm (no learnable params) |
| **Position encoding** | Learned absolute embeddings | RoPE (rotary, relative) |
| **Attention** | Multi-head (n_head = n_kv_head) | GQA (n_kv_head ≤ n_head) |
| **QKV projection** | Single combined c_attn | Separate W_Q, W_K, W_V |
| **QK normalization** | None | RMSNorm on Q and K |
| **Attention mask** | Full causal | Sliding window (alternating) |
| **MLP activation** | GELU | ReLU-squared |
| **Bias** | Yes (in all linear layers) | No (nowhere) |
| **Weight tying** | lm_head = wte^T | Untied (separate lm_head) |
| **Residual** | x + block(x) | λ_r·x + λ_0·x₀ + block(x) |
| **Value embeddings** | None | Alternating layers |
| **Logit bounding** | None | Softcap: c·tanh(logits/c) |

Every change was motivated by a specific problem. Simpler normalization (RMSNorm). Better position handling (RoPE). Less memory (GQA). Stable training (QK norm, softcapping). Sparser features (ReLU-squared). Gradient highways (λ scaling).

